    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-18T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-18T21:00:00-05:00" n="717"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d717">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13931: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-19T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 19, 1937—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 19—1 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>32. A telegram filed by Paxton at Loyang on January 18, 11 p.m. states: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>That Barrett and Wang<note n="14" xml:id="d717fn14">Wang Kwong, of the
                                Chinese Foreign Office.</note> returned from Sian to Loyang without
                            foreign passengers.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>That 75 foreigners had already left Sian with Scott and had proceeded
                            to Tungkwan.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>That Scott had returned to Sian after having carried out the
                            evacuation.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>That the foregoing information had been confirmed by telephone call
                            from Paxton to Swenson at Tungkwan.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>That Barrett and Fraser were returning to Sian to evacuate Scott and
                            perhaps five British and three Russian[s] who still remained
                            there.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The evacuation from Sian was presumably effected by bus in accordance with a plan
                    arranged by Peck and Captain Scott with Sian authorities during Peck’s visit
                    there.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, Peiping, Hankow, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
